In the Python implementation of `temporal_memory.py` it is possible to set the maximum number of synapses per segment and the maximum number of segments per cell at runtime via [initialization argments](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/master/src/nupic/research/temporal_memory.py#L54-L55). However, the C++ implementation [does not accept these arguments](https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/master/src/nupic/algorithms/TemporalMemory.cpp#L54) and instead always uses the hard coded [defaults](https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/master/src/nupic/algorithms/Connections.hpp#L239-L240).

Discovered while implementing numenta/nupic#2980

@chetan51

Right now we're trying to use the `RAVEN_IGNORE_EXCEPTIONS` flask config variable with a list of strings (instead of exception classes) and we're getting a crash.  The [advanced usage documentation](https://docs.getsentry.com/hosted/clients/python/advanced/) shows that we can specify a list of strings to the client for the `ignore_exception` parameter, but it doesn't seem like the Flask module takes advantage it, instead it favors its own check. (The following is just pseudocode, but it demonstrates the kind of check done).

    def handle_exception(exception, config_ignore_list):
        for exc in config_ignore_list:
            if isinstance(exception, exc):
               return

If you use a list of strings, you'll get a crash when you pass a string into `isinstance` as the `type` parameter. Unfortunately, using the list of exception classes would introduce a circular reference in our code, and restructuring everything to avoid that circular import would be difficult. 

I don't mind submitting a PR to fix this issue, but before I jump in I was hoping to see if I maybe I've missed something, or if there were any tips/approaches that you would like me to take.  I think that my approach would be to remove that check in favor of the `ignore_exceptions` parameter, and cast a provided list of exception classes to a list of strings to provide backwards compatibility. Does that sound sensible?

